\wg21_head(title={Rebasing \tt{<cmath>} on C23}){
\dl{
  \dt{Document number:} \dd{\docnum{D3935R2}}
  \dt{Date:}            \dd{\tt{2026-06-27}}
  \dt{Audience:}        \dd{LEWG}
  \dt{Project:}         \dd{ISO/IEC 14882 Programming Languages — C++, ISO/IEC JTC1/SC22/WG21}
  \dt{Reply-to:}        \dd{Jan Schultke <\mail{janschultke@gmail.com}>}
  \dt{GitHub Issue:}    \dd{\ref("https://wg21.link/P3935/github")}
  \dt{Source:}          \dd{\ref("https://github.com/eisenwave/cpp-proposals/blob/master/src/cmath-c23.cow")}
}
\hr
}

\Babstract{
Most of C++26 is based on C23, but the header \header{cmath}
is still based on C17.
There are many useful C23 \header{math.h} features that should be provided in C++.
}

\h2(listed=false){Contents}

\make_contents

\h2{Revision history}

\h3{Changes since R1}

\ul{
  \li{
    Removed \tcode{iscanonical} and \tcode{canonicalize} functions;
    see also \ref("#canonical-floating-point-representations-and-canonicalization")
  }
  \li{
    Made classification functions take their parameter by \tcode{const&};
    see also \ref("#classification-functions")
  }
  \li{
    Removed the \q{fully generic} narrow rounding function templates;
    see also \ref("#narrow-rounding-functions")
  }
  \li{
    Removed core language changes that define \q{canonical representation}
  }
  \li{
    Adjusted some wording in \ref("#c.math.narrow")
  }
}

\h3{Changes since R0}

\ul{
  \li{Removed \tcode{noexcept} from \tcode{std::fadd} and other proposed templates}
  \li{Added \ref("#no-simd-support")}
}

\h2{Introduction}

\ref("P3348R4") rebased the C++26 standard on C23;
it previously referred to C17.
However, this process was deliberately left incomplete:
some of the new C23 \header{math.h} features are only used by decimal floating-point types,
or they require core language changes, etc.

The goal of this proposal is to pull in all the new C23 \header{math.h} features
which are useful not only to decimal floating-point numbers.

Introducing decimal floating-point numbers into C++ is out-of scope.
That is, adding C's \tcode{_Decimal128} type as a \tcode{std::decimal128_t} alias
is not proposed,
and neither is any function intended to provide support for decimal floating-point types.

\header{simd} is also out-of-scope,
but expanding \header{simd} support for these new functions should be done in a future paper.

\h2{Design}

\h3{New functions}

The functions in the table below are proposed for inclusion in C++29.
The placeholder \tcode{\exposid{F}} is a shorthand for the
\tcode{\exposid{floating-point-type}} placeholder in \eelis{cmath.syn}.
In addition to the functions using an \tcode{\exposid{F}} placeholder,
single-type functions such as \tcode{float acospif(float)} are proposed,
but are not listed in the table for the sake of brevity;
refer to \ref("#wording") for the complete list.

\style{
  #new-functions {
    margin-left: auto;
    margin-right: auto;
  }
  #new-functions td {
    border-top: 1px solid var(--border-color);
  }
  #new-functions code {
    white-space: pre;
  }
}

\table(id="new-functions"){
  \tr{
    \th{Function}
    \th{ISO/IEC 60559 op.}
    \th{Returns}
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{bool issignaling(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{isSignaling}
    \td{
      \tcode{true} if and only if \tcode{x} is a signaling NaN
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{bool issubnormal(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{isSubnormal}
    \td{
      \tcode{true} if and only if \tcode{x} is subnormal
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{bool iszero(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{isZero}
    \td{
      \tcode{true} if and only if \tcode{x} is zero
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} acospi(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{acosPi}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \mrow{\mi{arccos}\mo(stretchy=false){(}\mi{x}\mo(stretchy=false){)}}
        \mo{÷}
        \mi{π}
      }}
      in the interval \math{\mrow{\mo{[}
        \mn{0}\mo{,}\mn{1}
      \mo{]}}}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} asinpi(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{asinPi}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \mrow{\mi{arcsin}\mo(stretchy=false){(}\mi{x}\mo(stretchy=false){)}}
        \mo{÷}
        \mi{π}
      }}
      in the interval \math{\mrow{
        \mo{[}
        \mo(form="prefix"){−}\mfrac{\mn{1}\mn{2}}\mo{,}
        \mo(form="prefix"){+}\mfrac{\mn{1}\mn{2}}\mo{]}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} atanpi(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{atanPi}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \mrow{\mi{arctan}\mo(stretchy=false){(}\mi{x}\mo(stretchy=false){)}}
        \mo{÷}
        \mi{π}
      }}
      in the interval \math{\mrow{\mo{[}
        \mo(form="prefix"){−}\mfrac{\mn{1}\mn{2}}\mo{,}
        \mo(form="prefix"){+}\mfrac{\mn{1}\mn{2}}
      \mo{]}}}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} atan2pi(\exposid{F} y, \exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{atan2Pi}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \mrow{\mi{atan2}\mo(stretchy=false){(}\mi{x}\mo{,}\mi{y}\mo(stretchy=false){)}}
        \mo{÷}
        \mi{π}
      }}
      in the interval \math{\mrow{\mo{[}
        \mo(form="prefix"){−}\mn{1}\mo{,}
        \mo(form="prefix"){+}\mn{1}
      \mo{]}}}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} cospi(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{cosPi}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \mi{cos}\mo(stretchy=false){(}
        \mi{x}\mo{×}\mi{π}
        \mo(stretchy=false){)}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} sinpi(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{sinPi}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \mi{sin}\mo(stretchy=false){(}
        \mi{x}\mo{×}\mi{π}
        \mo(stretchy=false){)}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} tanpi(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{tanPi}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \mi{tan}\mo(stretchy=false){(}
        \mi{x}\mo{×}\mi{π}
        \mo(stretchy=false){)}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} exp10(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{exp10}
    \td{
      \math{\msup{
        \mn{10}\mi{x}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} exp10m1(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{exp10m1}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \msup{\mn{10}\mi{x}}
        \mo{−}
        \mn{1}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} exp2m1(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{exp2m1}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \msup{\mn{2}\mi{x}}
        \mo{−}
        \mn{1}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} log10p1(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{log10p1}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \msub{\mi{log}\mn{10}}
        \mo(stretchy=false){(}
        \mn{1}\mo{+}\mi{x}
        \mo(stretchy=false){)}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} logp1(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{logp1}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \mi{log}\mo(stretchy=false){(}
        \mn{1}\mo{+}\mi{x}
        \mo(stretchy=false){)}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} log2p1(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{log2p1}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \msub{\mi{log}\mn{2}}
        \mo(stretchy=false){(}
        \mn{1}\mo{+}\mi{x}
        \mo(stretchy=false){)}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} compoundn(\exposid{F} x,
  long long n);}}
    \td{compound}
    \td{
      \math{\msup{
        \mrow{
          \mo(stretchy=false){(}
          \mn{1}\mo{+}\mi{x}
          \mo(stretchy=false){)}
        }
        \mi{n}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} pown(\exposid{F} x, long long n);}}
    \td{pown}
    \td{
      \math{\msup{
        \mi{x}
        \mi{n}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} powr(\exposid{F} y, \exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{powr}
    \td{
      \math{\msup{
        \mi{e}
        \mrow{
          \mi{y}
          \msub{\mo{log}\mi{e}}
          \mi{x}
        }
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} rootn(\exposid{F} x, long long n);}}
    \td{rootn}
    \td{
      \math{\msup{
        \mi{x}
        \mfrac{\mn{1}\mi{n}}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} rsqrt(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{rSqrt}
    \td{
      \math{\mfrac{
        \mn{1}
        \msqrt{\mi{x}}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} roundeven(\exposid{F} x);}}
    \td{roundToIntegralTiesToEven}
    \td{
      \tcode{x} rounded to the nearest integer,\br
      rounding halfway cases to even
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} fromfp(\exposid{F} x, int rnd,
  unsigned width);}}
    \td{convertToInteger…}
    \td{
      \tcode{x} rounded to a signed \tcode{width}-bit integer,\br
      or NaN if \tcode{x} is not in range;\br
      \tcode{rnd} is the rounding mode
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} ufromfp(\exposid{F} x, int rnd,
  unsigned width);}}
    \td{convertToInteger…}
    \td{
      \tcode{x} rounded to an unsigned \tcode{width}-bit integer,\br
      or NaN if \tcode{x} is not in range;\br
      \tcode{rnd} is the rounding mode
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} fromfpx(\exposid{F} x, int rnd,
  unsigned width);}}
    \td{convertToIntegerExact…}
    \td{
      \tcode{fromfp(x, rnd, width)};\br
      may also raise \tt{FE_INEXACT}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} ufromfpx(\exposid{F} x, int rnd,
  unsigned width);}}
    \td{convertToIntegerExact…}
    \td{
      \tcode{ufromfp(x, rnd, width)};\br
      may also raise \tt{FE_INEXACT}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} fmaximum_mag(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);}}
    \td{maximumMagnitude}
    \td{
      the value with greater magnitude,\br
      or \tcode{fmaximum(x, y)}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} fminimum_mag(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);}}
    \td{minimumMagnitude}
    \td{
      the value with greater magnitude,\br
      or \tcode{fminimum(x, y)}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} fmaximum_mag_num(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);}}
    \td{maximumMagnitudeNumber}
    \td{
      the value with greater magnitude,\br
      or \tcode{fmaximum_num(x, y)}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} fminimum_mag_num(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);}}
    \td{minimumMagnitudeNumber}
    \td{
      the value with greater magnitude,\br
      or \tcode{fminimum_num(x, y)}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{
      \tcode{float fadd(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);
double dadd(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);}
    }
    \td{addition}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{\mi{x}\mo{+}\mi{y}}}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{
      \tcode{float fsub(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);
double dsub(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);}
    }
    \td{subtraction}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{\mi{x}\mo{−}\mi{y}}}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{
      \tcode{float fmul(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);
double dmul(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);}
    }
    \td{multiplication}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{\mi{x}\mo{×}\mi{y}}}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{
      \tcode{float fdiv(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);
double ddiv(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y);}
    }
    \td{division}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{\mi{x}\mo{÷}\mi{y}}}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{
      \tcode{float ffma(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y, \exposid{F} z);
double dfma(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y, \exposid{F} z);}
    }
    \td{fusedMultiplyAdd}
    \td{
      \math{\mrow{
        \mo{(}\mi{x}\mo{×}\mi{y}\mo{)}
        \mo{+}\mi{z}
      }}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{
      \tcode{float fsqrt(\exposid{F} x);
double dsqrt(\exposid{F} x);}
    }
    \td{squareRoot}
    \td{
      \math{\msqrt{\mi{x}}}
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{bool iseqsig(\exposid{F} x, \exposid{F} y)}}
    \td{compareSignalingEqual}
    \td{
      \tcode{true} if \tcode{x} and \tcode{y} are equal and\br
      \tcode{false} otherwise
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{bool totalorder(
  const \exposid{F}* x,
  const \exposid{F}* y);}}
    \td{totalOrder}
    \td{
      \tcode{true} if totalOrder(\tcode{*x}, \tcode{*y})
      is true,\br
      as per ISO/IEC 60559
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{bool totalordermag(
  const \exposid{F}* x,
  const \exposid{F}* y);}}
    \td{totalOrderMag}
    \td{
      \tcode{true} if totalOrderMag(\tcode{*x}, \tcode{*y})
      is true,\br
      as per ISO/IEC 60559
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{\exposid{F} getpayload(const \exposid{F}* x);}}
    \td{getPayload}
    \td{
      the NaN payload in \tcode{*x},\br
      or -1 if the \tcode{*x} is not a NaN
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{int setpayload(
  \exposid{F}* res, \exposid{F} pl);}}
    \td{setPayload}
    \td{
      zero if the NaN payload in \tcode{*res} could be set,\br
      and nonzero value otherwise
    }
  }
  \tr{
    \td{\tcode{int setpayloadsig(
  \exposid{F}* res, \exposid{F} pl);}}
    \td{setPayloadSig}
    \td{
      same as \tcode{setpayload},\br
      but creates sNaN instead of qNan
    }
  }
}

As can be seen, all of these implement an ISO/IEC 60559 operation,
and even if they didn't,
they would be useful solely for the purpose of C compatibility.

All functions below \tcode{iseqsig} are specific to ISO/IEC 60559,
and are only provided by C23 for types that adhere to ISO/IEC 60559.
The same restriction should be inherited by C++;
otherwise e.g. \tcode{totalorder} would require us to define a total order
for every possible format of floating-point type,
which seems unreasonable.

All new functions should be \tcode{constexpr} because
none of them have a strong dependence on the current rounding mode
or floating-point environment.

\h4{No SIMD support}

At this time,
no SIMD overloads are proposed because
\ul{
  \li{
    it would significantly broaden the scope of this proposal
    beyond just establishing C23 compatibility,
  }
  \li{
    the function signatures are not obvious in many cases
    (would \tcode{fromfp} take a \tcode{basic_vec} of rounding modes?), and
  }
  \li{
    there is no particular urgency to do it all in one paper;
    it does not result in a broken specification,
    just in some missing nice-to-have features for \header{simd}.
  }
}

\h4{Narrow rounding functions}

The narrow rounding functions (such as \tcode{fadd})
are the most complex part of this proposal,
and they are somewhat unergonomic;
even the \header{tgmath.h} versions require the user to specify the return type
as a prefix (\tt{f}, \tt{d}, \tt{f32}, …) as part of the function name.
This makes it difficult to write generic code.

\Bnote{
To solve this,
R1 of the paper proposed additional function templates such as:

\cppblock{
template<class T, class F1, class F2>
  constexpr T fadd(F1 x, F2 y);
}

However, this would create a strange overload set with the existing \tcode{fadd} functions
(where the \tcode{f} prefix indicates \tcode{float}).
Notable, the integer overloads of \header{cmath} functions
are typically implemented function templates,
and we don't really want to create an overload set with those.

There is also no other obvious name we could use.
We may not want to create overload sets with \tcode{std::fma}, \tcode{std::sqrt},
and \tcode{std::div},
and use up some extremely valuable names like \tcode{std::add}.
}

Anyway, we provide only the functionality that is necessary for C compatibility,
which is
\ul{
  \li{
    concrete functions like \tcode{std::faddl}, \tcode{std::f32sqrtf64}, etc., and
  }
  \li{
    overloaded functions like \tcode{std::fadd}
    which are meant to emulate the behavior of the \header{tgmath.h} macro
    by selecting between the \tcode{long double}→\tcode{float} and \tcode{double}→\tcode{float}
    overloads.
  }
}

\h4{Canonical floating-point representations and canonicalization}

Earlier revisions of this paper also included the functions
\tcode{iscanonical} and \tcode{canonicalize},
which can technically be called with floating-point arguments of any radix,
but are only useful for decimal floating-point types.

These have been removed because they should be included as part
of a future proposal that provides support for decimal floating-point types in general.
Providing them now would also raise the question of what a \q{canonical representation} is,
within the C++ core language, which is scope creep.

\h4{ISO/IEC-60559-specific functions}

Some of the functions in the table are optionally provided:
\tcode{totalorder}, \tcode{totalordermag},
\tcode{getpayload}, \tcode{setpayload}, and \tcode{setpayloadsig}.
That is because it doesn't make sense to ask for the NaN payload
of a floating-point number
where NaN isn't supported.
Universal behavior for these functions would need to be defined, and
C currently just delegates to the ISO/IEC 60559 operations.

\Bnote{
These functions accept a parameter by pointer rather than by value
because loading a floating-point value into an argument may change the value
and inadvertently alter the behavior of the function.
See also \ref("#classification-functions") for discussion of basically the same problem.
}

A notable difference between the C23 feature and what's proposed
is that C23 defines these functions only if \tcode{__STDC_WANT_IEC_60559_EXT__} is defined
before \header{math.h} is included.
In C++, whether the functions are defined depends solely on whether
\tcode{std::numeric_limits<T>::is_iec559} is \tcode{true} for the type \tcode{T}.
Requiring C++ users to define the macro
would stray too far from \q{idiomatic} C++ code,
and it's unclear how this is supposed to work with modules and/or with \tcode{import std;}.

The functions have to exist in the runtime math library anyway,
so the benefit of them being opt-int in a header is unclear.

\h3(id="classification-functions"){Making classification functions take by \tt{const&}}

A pre-existing defect is that classification functions such as \tcode{signbit}
take their parameter by value.
The problem is that when lvalue-to-rvalue conversion takes place,
only the \em{value}, not the exact bit pattern (value representation)
of an object is being carried by prvalues.
In terms of hardware, it's possible that loading from memory into a register
may perform canonicalization, flush to zero, or alter NaN payloads.
This is a problem because those changes could alter the result of functions such
\tcode{signbit}, \ins{\tcode{issignaling}}, \tcode{isnormal}, \ins{\tcode{issubnormal}}, etc.
(essentially of any function).

After extensive CWG discussion of the problem,
it was suggested that the functions should take their parameter by \tcode{const&}.
The existing incompatibility between C and C++ was also discussed in SG22
and resulted in some opposition to R1 of this paper.
This means that
\ul{
  \li{
    existing functions are updated,
    to e.g. \tcode{signbit(const \exposid{floating-point-type}&)}, and
  }
  \li{
    new functions are added,
    such as \tcode{iszero(const \exposid{floating-point-type}&)}.
  }
}

Taking \tcode{const&} allows inspecting the original object
irrespective of what changes lvalue-to-rvalue conversion would perform.

\Bnote{
In C, this problem is solved by defining these functions as macros,
without any concrete overloads like \tcode{signbitf(float)}.
If loading from memory into an argument would change the value,
the macro could be defined so that it inspects the original object when given an lvalue.
}

This is not a breaking change because any expression can be passed by \tcode{const&}
just as well as by value.

\h3{New macros}

Besides the new functions,
there are also macros which are pulled in from C23.

\Bnote{
The \tcode{int rnd} parameter in functions such as \tcode{fromfp}
corresponds to one of \tt{FP_INT_*} rounding direction macros.
}

The block below lists all new macros
(not yet including the \tcode{float\placeholder{N}_t} placeholder versions):

\cppblock{
// rounding direction macros
FP_INT_UPWARD
FP_INT_DOWNWARD
FP_INT_TOWARDZERO
FP_INT_TONEARESTFROMZERO
FP_INT_TONEAREST

// indicates that the respective function is "fast"
FP_FAST_FADD
FP_FAST_FADDL
FP_FAST_DADDL
FP_FAST_FSUB
FP_FAST_FSUBL
FP_FAST_DSUBL
FP_FAST_FMUL
FP_FAST_FMULL
FP_FAST_DMULL
FP_FAST_FDIV
FP_FAST_FDIVL
FP_FAST_DDIVL
FP_FAST_FSQRT
FP_FAST_FSQRTL
FP_FAST_DSQRTL
FP_FAST_FFMA
FP_FAST_FFMAL
FP_FAST_DFMAL
}

\h3{New declarations for \tcode{float\placeholder{N}_t}}

C23 also provides a suffixed version of all the common common mathematical
functions with \tcode{f\placeholder{N}} suffix and with
\tcode{float\placeholder{N}_t} parameters.
While these are not particularly useful considering that the user can (and probably should)
call the overloaded functions,
the current design direction is for C++ to inherit suffixed functions;
we already do so for \tcode{sqrtf} and \tcode{sqrtl}.
It would make porting C code to C++ and vice versa needlessly difficult
if the suffixed functions only existed in one standard,
for seemingly no technical reason.

\Bnote{
In the case of the narrow rounding functions,
C23 also has
\ul{
  \li{prefixed generic functions such as \tcode{f32add}, and}
  \li{prefixed concrete functions such as \tcode{f32addf64},}
}
as explained above.
}

The pattern of always providing the suffixed versions is only broken by
\tcode{fminimum}, \tcode{fminimum_num}, \tcode{fmaximum}, and \tcode{fmaximum_num}.
These functions were added to C++26 by \ref("P3008R6"),
mostly to specify the behavior of atomic floating-point minimum/maximum
in terms of the C23 functions.
There is no technical reason why the suffixed versions shouldn't also be provided,
and the paper does not discuss this option.

\h2{Implementation experience}

All non-template additions are taken from C23,
and most have been implemented in gnulibc.

The new narrow rounding function templates simply dispatch to some
non-template overload based on the template argument \tcode{T}.

Some of the proposed functions are also implemented in Clang as builtins,
such as \tcode{__builtin_roundeven}.
Some of them are implementable using existing builtins,
such as \tcode{__builtlin_isfpclass}.
Some of these Clang builtins are also \tcode{constexpr}.

\h2{Wording}

The changes are relative to \ref("N5014").

\h3(show_number=false){[version.syn]}

Add a feature-test macro to \eelis{version.syn} as follows:

\Bins{
\itemdecl{
#define __cpp_lib_cmath 20XXXXL //\serif{ also in \tt{<cmath>}, \tt{<cstdlib>}}
}
}

\editnote{
Although the proposal also adds a \tcode{__STDC_VERSION_MATH_H__} macro from C23,
this cannot be reliably used to detect the new functions;
it could have also been leaked through a \header{math.h} header from somewhere,
without e.g. \tcode{std::roundeven} actually existing.
}

Bump the feature-test macro for mathematical special functions:

\Bdiff{
\itemdecl{
#define __cpp_lib_math_special_functions \del{201603L} \ins{20XXXXL} //\serif{ also in \tt{<cmath>}}
}
}

\editnote{
This queries existence of new overloads such as \tcode{ellint_3f32}.
}

