Change \eelis{cmath.syn#1} as follows:

\Bdiff{
The contents and meaning of the header \header{cmath} are a subset of
the C standard library header \header{math.h}
and only the declarations shown in the synopsis above are present,
with the addition of
a three-dimensional hypotenuse function,
a linear interpolation function, and
the mathematical special functions described in \eelis{sf.cmath}.
}

Change \eelis{cmath.syn#2} as follows:

\Bdiff{
\del{For each function with at least one parameter of type \tcode{\floating_point_typ},
the implementation provides an overload
for each cv-unqualified floating-point type\iref{basic.fundamental}}
\ins{Multiple functions above are specified using a type placeholder,
for which the implementation providese an overload for each type in a set,}
where all uses of \del{\tcode{\floating_point_typ}} \ins{the type placeholder}
in the function signature
are replaced with that floating-point type.
\ul{
  \li{\ins{
    For the type placeholder \tcode{\floating_point_typ},
    the set of types is all cv-unqualified floating-point types.
  }}
  \li{\ins{
    For the type placeholder \tcode{\exposid{double-type}},
    the set of types is \tcode{double} and \tcode{long double}.
  }}
  \li{\ins{
    For the type placeholder \tcode{float\placeholder{N}_t},
    the set of types is
    \tcode{float16_t}, \tcode{float32_t}, \tcode{float64_t}, and \tcode{float128_t},
    if defined.
    The \tcode{\placeholder{N}} placeholder in the function name is replaced
    with the corresponding width in the type name.
  }}
}
}

Insert a new item immediately following \eelis{cmath.syn#2}:

\Bins{
¶
Let \tcode{\exposid{common-floating-point-type}} and
\tcode{\exposid{common-double-type}}
be the following exposition-only alias templates:

\itemdecl{
template<class... Ts>
  using \exposid{common-floating-point-type} = \seebelow;
template<class... Ts>
  using \exposid{common-double-type} = \seebelow;
}

\itemdescr{
¶
\constraints
Each type in the pack \tcode{Ts} is a
cv-unqualified arithmetic type\iref{basic.fundamental}.

¶
Let \tcode{R} be defined as follows:
\ul{
  \li{
    For \tcode{\exposid{common-floating-point-type}},
    let \tcode{R} be the floating-point type with the
    greatest floating-point conversion rank and
    greatest floating-point conversion subrank among the types in \tcode{Ts},
    where integer types are considered to have
    the same floating-point conversion rank as \tcode{double}.
  }
  \li{
    For \tcode{\exposid{common-double-type}},
    let \tcode{R} be \tcode{long double} if any of the types in \tcode{Ts}
    is \tcode{long double}, and
    \tcode{double} otherwise.
  }
}

¶
\mandates
\tcode{R} is defined.

¶
\result
\tcode{R}.
}
}

\editnote{
\tcode{\exposid{common-floating-point-type}} is just following the existing
semantics of \eelis{cmath.syn#3} in the form of an exposition-only alias template.

\tcode{\exposid{common-double-type}} is meant to emulate
the behavior of the \header{tgmath.h} macros \tcode{fadd}, \tcode{fsub}, etc.

For \tcode{dadd}, \tcode{dsub}, etc. no such thing is necessary because without
decimal floating-point types,
the behavior is always to convert all arguments to \tcode{long double}.
}

Change \eelis{cmath.syn#3} as follows:

\Bdiff{
For each function with at least one parameter
\del{of type \tcode{\floating_point_typ}}
\ins{declared with a type placeholder,}
other than \tcode{abs},
the implementation also provides additional overloads sufficient to ensure that,
if every argument corresponding to a
\del{\tcode{\floating_point_typ}} \ins{type placeholder}
parameter has arithmetic type,
then every such argument is effectively cast to
\del{the floating-point type
with the greatest floating-point conversion rank and
greatest floating-point conversion subrank among the types of all such arguments,
where arguments of integer type are considered to have
the same floating-point conversion rank as \tcode{double}}
\ul{
  \li{
    \ins{\tcode{\exposid{common-double-type}<Args...>} if the type placeholder is
    \tcode{\exposid{double-type}}, and}
  }
  \li{
    \ins{\tcode{\exposid{common-floating-point-type}<Args...>} otherwise.}
  }
}
If \del{no such floating-point type with the greatest rank and subrank exists}
\ins{that specialization of the alias template is ill-formed},
then overload resolution does not result in a usable candidate\iref{over.match.general}
from the overloads provided by the implementation.
}

Add a new paragraphs immediately following \eelis{cmath.syn#3}:

\Bins{
The implementation may provide additional overloads of
\tcode{\placeholder{p}add},
\tcode{\placeholder{p}sub},
\tcode{\placeholder{p}mul},
\tcode{\placeholder{p}div},
\tcode{\placeholder{p}fma}, and
\tcode{\placeholder{p}sqrt},
for any prefix \tcode{\placeholder{p}},
with parameters of cv-unqualified arithmetic types
to ensure consistent behavior with the corresponding macro
in C header \header{tgmath.h}.
}

\editnote{
While the implementation is generally free to provide additional overloads,
this is not allowed to alter the behavior of a conforming program.
If an implementation provided an extended floating-point type \tcode{_Decimal128},
\tcode{dadd} would need to convert arguments of type \tcode{_Decimal128}
to \tcode{long double},
but the C23 behavior is to call \tcode{daddd128}.

This would not be the case if \tcode{_Decimal128} was a compiler extension,
in which case the program isn't standard C++ anyway,
and the implementation can do whatever it wants.
}

\Bins{
The functions whose names begin with
\tcode{totalorder}, \tcode{totalordermag}, \tcode{getpayload}, or \tcode{setpayload}
are only provided if \tcode{numeric_limits<T>::is_iec559} is \tcode{true}
for the floating-point type \tcode{T} in the function signature
(possibly following the placeholder substitution described above).
}

\h3(show_number=false){[c.math.narrow]}

Add a new subclause as follows:

\Bins{
\cowel_html_element("h3"){Narrowing operations \stable_ref{c.math.narrow}}

\itemdecl{
constexpr float    f\placeholder{op}(\exposid{double-type} x /* ... */);
constexpr double   d\placeholder{op}(long double x /* ... */);
constexpr float\placeholder{N}_t f\placeholder{N}\placeholder{op}(\seebelow x /* ... */);
constexpr float\placeholder{N}_t f\placeholder{N}\placeholder{op}f\placeholder{M}(float\placeholder{M}_t x /* ... */);
}

\itemdescr{
¶
Let \tcode{\placeholder{op}} be a placeholder for
\tcode{add}, \tcode{sub}, \tcode{mul}, \tcode{div}, \tcode{fma}, or \tcode{sqrt}.

¶
For each of the functions
\tcode{f\placeholder{N}\placeholder{op}} and
\tcode{f\placeholder{N}\placeholder{op}f\placeholder{M}},
the implementation provides an overload for every
pair \tcode{\placeholder{N}} and \tcode{\placeholder{M}}
if \tcode{\placeholder{N}} < \tcode{\placeholder{M}} and the aliases
\tcode{float\placeholder{N}_t} and \tcode{float\placeholder{M}_t} are defined,
where every placeholder \tcode{\placeholder{N}} and \tcode{\placeholder{M}}
in the function signature is replaced with the corresponding integers.

¶
For each function \tcode{\placeholder{f\placeholder{M}\placeholder{op}f\placeholder{N}}},
the implementation also defines a macro
\tcode{FP_FAST_F\placeholder{M}\placeholder{up}F\placeholder{N}},
where \tcode{\placeholder{up}} is \tcode{\placeholder{op}} in uppercase.

¶
\effects
Each of the overloads
\ul{
  \li{
    \tcode{f\placeholder{op}} and \tcode{d\placeholder{op}}
    where the \tcode{\exposid{double-type}} is \tcode{double}
    has the same behavior as the C function with the same name;
  }
  \li{
    \tcode{f\placeholder{op}} and \tcode{d\placeholder{op}}
    where the \tcode{\exposid{double-type}} is \tcode{long double}
    has the same behavior as
    \tcode{f\placeholder{op}l} and \tcode{d\placeholder{op}l}, respectively; and
  }
  \li{
    \tcode{f\placeholder{N}\placeholder{op}}
    has the same behavior as the corresponding function
    \tcode{f\placeholder{N}\placeholder{op}f\placeholder{M}}
    with the same parameter types.
  }
}

¶
\example{
If only the aliases
\tcode{float32_t}, \tcode{float64_t}, and \tcode{float128_t} are defined
in \header{stdfloat},
for the \tcode{sqrt} operation,
the implementation provides the following declarations:
\itemdecl{
#define FP_FAST_FSQRT \exposid{see above}
#define FP_FAST_FSQRTL \exposid{see above}
#define FP_FAST_DSQRTL \exposid{see above}
#define FP_FAST_F32SQRTF64 \exposid{see above}
#define FP_FAST_F32SQRTF128 \exposid{see above}
#define FP_FAST_F64SQRTF128 \exposid{see above}

constexpr float fsqrt(double x);
constexpr float fsqrt(long double x);
constexpr float fsqrt(long double x);
constexpr double dsqrt(long double x);

constexpr float32_t f32sqrt(float64_t x);
constexpr float32_t f32sqrt(float128_t x);
constexpr float64_t f64sqrt(float128_t x);
constexpr float32_t f32sqrtf64(float64_t x);
constexpr float32_t f32sqrtf128(float128_t x);
constexpr float64_t f64sqrtf128(float128_t x);
}
Additionally,
the implementation provides overloads that allow calling
\tcode{fsqrt},
\tcode{f32sqrt}, and
\tcode{f64sqrt} with arguments of integral type.
}
}
}

\h3(show_number=false){[sf.cmath]}

For every overload set in this subclause,
add the same overload as shown in the synopsis changes above:

\Bex{
Change the declaration in \eelis{sf.cmath.assoc.laguerre} as follows:
\Bdiff{
\itemdecl{
\floating_point_typ assoc_laguerre(unsigned n, unsigned m, \floating_point_typ x);
float               assoc_laguerref(unsigned n, unsigned m, float x);
long double         assoc_laguerrel(unsigned n, unsigned m, long double x);
\ins{float\placeholder{N}_t            assoc_laguerref\placeholder{N}(unsigned n, unsigned m, float\placeholder{N}_t x);}
}
}
}

